---
description: "FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md file structure, grocery list formatting, meal headings, quick read codenames, H5 H6 system, archiving weeks, cooked checkmarks, markdown task lists"
alwaysApply: false
---
# FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK Current Week Structure

Standards for how `FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md` serves as the source of truth for the current week's meal plan.

**Context loading:** If not already loaded, read `brainstorming/idea-basis/cooking-identity.md` for the cook's profile before writing or editing meals.

**Reference examples:** Recent files in `archive/` are the canonical source for current structure (most recent week wins). Do not reference any deleted prototype documents.

<rule>
name: foodoftheweek-current-week
description: Defines the structure and lifecycle of FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md as the live meal plan document

purpose:
  primary: "FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md is the single source of truth for the website"
  visibility: "Content is published to the live Astro site"
  audience: "Family members viewing the meal plan"

required_structure:
  order:
    1: "Week heading (# Week of [Date Range])"
    2: "Grocery List section (## Grocery List)"
    3: "Meal sections (## [Meal Name] - no numbering, no colon)"
  
  heading_levels:
    week_title: "# (H1) - Only one per FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md"
    major_sections: "## (H2) - For Grocery List and each Meal"
    grocery_categories: "### (H3) - For Produce, Staples, etc."
    meal_subsections: "### (H3) - Optional for Instructions, Notes, etc."
    quick_read_codename: "##### (H5) - Quick read codename (immediately after the meal H2)"
    quick_read_briefing: "###### (H6) - Sous chef night briefing fragment (directly follows the codename). Tells the sous chef team the structure of THEIR night in short phrases: prep tasks, timing pegs (5:30 boil, bag in bath PM), and finishing handoffs. NOT a chef hands-on time metric."

grocery_list_format:
  section_heading: "## Grocery List"
  
  common_categories:
    - "### Produce"
    - "### Protein"
    - "### Staples"
    - "### Pantry"
  notes:
    - "Only include categories that have items -- not all are required every week"
    - "Custom categories are allowed (e.g., ### Dairy, ### Frozens)"
    - "On-hand items go into their natural category with [x] -- no separate 'Already On Hand' section"
    - "Flavor cabinet staples (soy sauce, oils, vinegars, salt, spices always in stock) are omitted entirely"
  
  item_format:
    to_buy: "- [ ] Item name - quantity/details"
    on_hand: "- [x] Item name"
    
  notes:
    - "Use markdown task list syntax for checkbox functionality"
    - "Unchecked [ ] = need to buy; checked [x] = already on hand"
    - "Including on-hand items gives a complete picture of what goes into the week"

meal_format:
  section_heading: "## [Meal Name]"
  note: "No numbering (Meal 1, Meal 2) and no colon in heading"
  quick_read:
    codename: "##### [Codename]"
    briefing: "###### [Sous chef night briefing -- short fragment]"
    placement: "Appears immediately after the meal H2 heading"
    audience: "The H6 line is for the sous chef team. The H5 line is for everyone."
    notes:
      - "Codename populates hero summary rows; the H6 briefing tells the sous chef what their night looks like."
      - "Codename is required for parser extraction; H6 briefing is optional but recommended."
      - "H6 briefing format: short phrases separated by ` + `, ordered by when the sous chef does each thing. Examples: `prep + salad/gremolata + 5:30 boil`, `prep + curry simmer + 5:30 rice`, `bag in bath PM + 5:30 quinoa + cast iron sear`."
      - "Use clock pegs only when timing matters (e.g. `5:30 rice` for the rice cooker start). Do NOT include chef hands-on time -- that metric is irrelevant to the planning."
      - "Do NOT use the stopwatch symbol `⏱`. It was a deprecated convention that confused the audience. The H6 line is sous chef workflow, not a chef metric."
      - "BatchDay H6 follows the same pattern: it briefs the batcher on the structure of prep, e.g. `saturday: cube + bag pork into bath / sunday: chicken bag + cai jars`. Not a duration."
    
    codename_types:
      WokNight:
        pattern: "##### WokNight"
        meaning: "Wok-sequenced meal -- 1-3 quick dishes fired in a row. The wok is the primary tool."
        examples:
          - "##### WokNight"

      ChefDish:
        pattern: "##### ChefDish[+*]"
        meaning: "Chef is doing this solo -- no meaningful delegation. Plus signs signal the chef's own memory-jog level."
        plus_scale:
          none: "Straightforward. No day-ahead work. Cook and plate."
          one_plus: "Some day-ahead or timing-sensitive effort required."
          two_plus: "Significant day-ahead AND hands-on evening effort."
        examples:
          - "##### ChefDish"
          - "##### ChefDish+"
      
      Prep_and_Heat:
        pattern: "##### Prep&Heat[+*]"
        meaning: "Family-delegated prep with oven or stovetop finish. Classic weeknight delegation pattern."
        plus_scale:
          none: "Simple prep and heat."
          one_plus: "Some day-ahead work or longer hands-on prep."
      
      BatchDay:
        pattern: "##### BatchDay"
        meaning: "Sunday batch prep session. Not a meal -- a prep day."
        examples:
          - "##### BatchDay"
  
  field_format:
    heading: "#### [Field Name]:"
    format: "H4 heading with colon on its own line, followed by field content starting on the next line"
    standard_fields:
      - "#### Anchor:"
      - "#### Fan:"
      - "#### Cai:"
      - "#### Soup:  (optional, only include if soup is on the table)"
    notes:
      - "Field names are arbitrary; consecutive H4 headings are grouped as one visual card"
      - "Do not include the value on the same line as the heading"
      - "Anchor = the louder cai / primary protein dish. Fan = the staple grain. Cai = shared dishes. Soup = soup if it's on the table; omit the field entirely on no-soup nights (do not write 'None')."
  
  instruction_format:
    structure: "Three-phase base format (see recipe-instruction-format.mdc). The Sous Chef phase can split into Prep + Assembly on heavy nights."
    base_phases:
      - "### Already Prepped"
      - "### Sous Chef - Assembly  (or split into ### Sous Chef - Prep + ### Sous Chef - Assembly)"
      - "### Chef - Wok Sequence  (or ### Chef - Cooking)"
    notes:
      - "H3 headings for distinct instruction sections (no inline values)"
      - "Phase names flex to match the night's technique (Wok Sequence, Cooking, etc.)"
      - "Already Prepped is a bulleted list of Sunday prep components used tonight"
      - "Sous Chef handles rice, reheating bags, fresh assembly"
      - "Chef handles hands-on cooking (wok, cast iron, oven)"
    sous_chef_split:
      when_to_split: "Heavy nights with multiple atomic prep tasks before the assembly work begins. Simple nights collapse to a single Sous Chef section."
      prep_section:
        label: "### Sous Chef - Prep"
        format: "Markdown task checklist (- [ ] format). Atomic prep tasks with light context. Can be grouped under bold sub-headers like `**Do these first:**` or grouped by tool/technique."
        examples:
          - "- [ ] Dice *1 large* **yellow onion** for the curry."
          - "- [ ] Slice *4-5* **garlic** cloves thin, set near the stove."
      assembly_section:
        label: "### Sous Chef - Assembly"
        format: "Composed cai builds with `**Bold dish name**:` and narrative instructions, plus timing pegs (5:30 boil, etc.)."
        examples:
          - "**Roman white bean salad**: into a serving bowl combine the **cannellini**, **rinsed diced white onion**..."
          - "At **5:30** fill the dutch oven with water, **salt it like the sea**, and bring to a boil."

  structure:
    meals: "Descriptive names only (## Meal Name)"
    fields: "H4 headings with colons for arbitrary field names"
    sections: "H3 headings for instruction sections"
    grouping: "Consecutive H4 fields → single visual card; each H3 → distinct section"
    cooked: "Use `## ✓ Meal Name` to mark cooked meals; avoid strikethroughs for this purpose"

template:
  reference: "Use the most recent file in archive/ as the canonical example. The skeleton below is a structural reference."
  skeleton: |
    # Week of [Month DD - DD, YYYY]
    
    ## Grocery List
    
    ### Produce
    - [ ] Item - quantity
    - [x] On-hand item
    
    ### Protein
    - [ ] Protein - amount (breakdown)
    
    ### Staples
    - [ ] Item
    - [x] On-hand item
    
    ### Pantry
    - [ ] Specialty item (lasts months)
    - [x] On-hand item
    
    ---
    
    ## Sunday Prep
    
    ##### BatchDay
    ###### saturday: pork bath / sunday: chicken bag + cai jars
    
    ### Prep Checklist
    - [ ] Task 1
    - [ ] Task 2
    
    ### Workflow
    [Narrative explaining the staging across days/hours]
    
    ### Protein Bags
    [Portioning, seasoning, and storage for each protein use]
    
    ### Cai Bags
    [Detailed instructions for each sous vide / pickle / marinade / no-heat component]
    
    ### Soup Bases (optional)
    [Concentrated soup base instructions, if soup is part of the week]
    
    ---
    
    ## [Meal Name]
    
    ##### Codename
    ###### prep + bean salad + 5:30 boil
    
    #### Anchor:
    [Primary protein dish -- the louder cai]
    
    #### Fan:
    [Staple grain or noodle]
    
    #### Cai:
    [Supporting shared dishes]
    
    #### Soup:
    [Optional -- include only if soup is on the table; soup is no longer assumed]
    
    ### Already Prepped
    - **Component** from Sunday.
    
    ### Sous Chef - Prep
    - [ ] Atomic prep task 1
    - [ ] Atomic prep task 2
    
    ### Sous Chef - Assembly
    [Composed cai builds with **Bold name**: instructions, plus timing pegs like 5:30 rice]
    
    ### Chef - Cooking
    [Hands-on cooking paragraphs ending with **Table**: layout]

lifecycle:
  active_period: "One week (typically Sunday to Sunday or Monday to Saturday)"
  
  archiving_process:
    when: "After the week ends"
    manual_step: true
    
    steps:
      1: "Copy entire FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md content"
      2: "Create new file: archive/YYYYMMDDsummary.md"
      3: "Paste content into archive file"
      4: "Update FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md with next week's content"
    
    filename_format:
      pattern: "YYYYMMDDsummary.md"
      date_meaning: "Start date of the week"
      examples:
        - "20251207summary.md (Week starting December 7, 2025)"
        - "20251214summary.md (Week starting December 14, 2025)"

actions:
  - type: enforce
    when: "Creating or updating FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md"
    do:
      - "Use standardized heading structure"
      - "Only include grocery categories that have items"
      - "Do NOT number meals (no 'Meal 1:', 'Meal 2:', etc.)"
      - "Use descriptive meal names only (## [Meal Name])"
      - "Use H4 headings with colons for fields (#### Field: content)"
      - "Use H3 headings for instruction sections (### Section Name)"
      - "Add H5 codename + H6 timing lines immediately after each meal H2 heading"
      - "Mark cooked meals with `## ✓ Meal Name` instead of strikethrough"
      - "Maintain markdown task list format for grocery items"
      - "Use three-phase instruction format"
  
  - type: guide
    when: "User is ready to finalize weekly plan"
    do:
      - "Structure content according to template"
      - "Ensure week date is clear in H1"
      - "Verify grocery list has relevant categories (only those with items)"
      - "Format meals with required fields"
      - "Apply three-phase instruction structure"
  
  - type: remind
    when: "Week is ending"
    do:
      - "Suggest archiving current FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md"
      - "Provide correct filename format (YYYYMMDDsummary.md)"
      - "Confirm archive/ folder location"

validation:
  checklist:
    - "H1 heading with week date range present"
    - "Grocery List section with relevant categories (only those with items)"
    - "4-5 meal sections with H2 headings (no numbering, no colons)"
    - "Field blocks use H4 headings with colons (#### Field: content)"
    - "Instruction sections use H3 headings (### Section Name)"
    - "Consecutive H4 fields are grouped as one visual card"
    - "Markdown task list syntax used for grocery items"
    - "Instructions use three-phase format (Sous Chef may split into Prep + Assembly)"
    - "Quick read codename + sous chef briefing use H5/H6 immediately after the meal heading"
    - "H6 line is a sous chef workflow briefing fragment (no `⏱`, no chef hands-on time metric)"
    - "Cooked meals use a leading `✓` in the H2 title (no strikethrough)"

  section_separators:
    format: "--- (horizontal rule) between meal sections"
    purpose: "Visual separator in raw markdown for easier manual editing and scrolling"
    parser_behavior: "Silently ignored (hr tokens are not processed)"
    rendering: "Does NOT appear on the website"
    usage: "Optional but encouraged for raw readability"

examples:
  - correct_meal: |
      ## Mapo Tofu

      ##### WokNight
      ###### bag thaw + 5:30 rice + wok sequence

      #### Anchor:
      Mapo tofu with ground pork -- Sichuan, saucy, numbing-spicy

      #### Fan:
      White rice

      #### Cai:
      Dry-fried green beans (from Sunday bag, wok finish), smashed cucumber salad (fresh), soy eggs (from Sunday)

      ### Already Prepped

      - **Green beans** (sesame-dressed bag) in fridge from Sunday.
      - **Soy eggs** in marinade in fridge from Sunday.
      - **Ground pork** (mapo portion) in freezer from Sunday.

      ### Sous Chef - Assembly

      Start **rice** in the rice cooker. Thaw **ground pork** bag in warm water.

      ### Chef - Wok Sequence

      **Wok dish 1 -- Mapo tofu**: Heat wok, add oil. ...

      **Table**: **rice** in individual bowls. **Mapo tofu** center on the lazy susan. **Green beans**, **cucumber salad**, **soy eggs** in small shared dishes.
  
  - correct_grocery_category: |
      ### Produce
      - [ ] Napa cabbage - 1 large head
      - [ ] Green beans - 1.5 lbs
      - [x] Garlic
      - [x] Ginger
  
  - correct_filename: "archive/20251207summary.md"
  
  - incorrect_filename: "archive/week-of-dec-7.md"

metadata:
  priority: high
  version: 1.0
  scope: FOOD-OF-THE-WEEK.md structure and lifecycle

</rule>
